or graphics array' b'320x200 colors or 640x200 b/w, color palette, bad for the eyes.' b'ega: enhanced graphics array' b'640x350 colors from color palette [and some lower res]; some versions' b'could run at colors, bearable on the eyes.' b'vga: video graphics array*' b'320x200 at colors, 640x480 at colors, and some others, these two are' b'the most commonly used. all modes have a 256k clut, from a' b'18 to 24-bit {ibm} or a 32-bit {mac} color palette. mhz pixel clock' b'(mel martinez). monitors use analog input, incompatible with ttl signals' b'from ega/cga etc.' b'mcga: multi-color graphics array*' b'subset of vga that provides all the features of mda cga, but lacks some ega' b'and vga modes, like vga 640x480x16 (dictionary of computer terms-dct).' b'common on the initial ps/1 implementation from ibm and some ps/2 models.' b'svga: super vga*' b"this is not a standard in the way the others were, but instead was a 'catch" b"all' category for a group of video cards. as such, with each manufacturer" b'using their own implementation scheme, svga was chaos with people debating' b'as to what is svga and what is not. in an effort to make svga more of a' b'standard vesa was established and is used in the newer units, but things' b'are still a mess. video is either 512k or 1m [today], resolution' b'of 800x600 and 1024x768 at and colors are common, newer ones [since' b'1990] have the sierra hicolor ramdac, giving 15-bit colors at 800x600,' b'some of the very newer ones can do bits per pixel [usually' b'at 640x480]. speedwise, too much variation, some very slow [western digital' b'paradise based, for example], some very fast [s3 86c911 based, for example],' b'some are so-so [like tseng et4000, a very popular chipset]. some limiting' b"factors overcome by 40mhz vl bus 386's linear address mapping were:" b'8.33 mhz isa bus, at architecture where the cpu looks at the card through a' b'64k "window", etc.' b'other non-svga standards:' b'8514/a:' b"ibm's own standard, interlacing graphics accelerator with graphics functions" b'like linedraw, polygon fill, etc. in hardware. some clone implementations' b'from ati are the fastest video available today, though some clone models do' b'not have interlacing.' b'tms34010/34020: high end graphics co-processors, usually some' b'do 24-bit, speeds up vector-oriented graphics like cad.' b'xga: extended graphics array' b'newer and faster than 8514/a, only available for mca bus-based ps/2s, clones' b'are coming out soon. emulates vga, ega, and cga (dct). max resolution at' b'1024x768x8b, same as 8514/a, also some bpp modes.' b'xga-2' b'accelerates graphics functions up to times faster than standard vga in' b'windows and os/2, including line draws, bit and pixel-block transfers, area' b'fills, masking and x/y addressing. has an intelligent way to detect and co-' b'exist with other xga-2 cards, so multiple desktops like on the mac may not be' b'far away. since this is an architecture, its resolution and color depth' b"isn't fixed {ibm implements only 16-bit color, while other" b'companies can have 24-bit color through ibm technical licenses}. refresh' b'rates up to hz, ensures flicker free, rock solid images to reduce visual' b'discomfort, and is vga compatible. up to 1280x1024 on os/2.' b'*some monitor types usable by mac-see mac section above for specific details.' b'' b'expansion' b'both mac ibm' b'scsi: only external device expansion interface common to both mac and ibm.' b'allows the use of any device: hard drive, printer, scanner, nubus card' b'expansion {mac plus only}, some monitors, and cd-rom.' b'main problem: there are a lot of external devices which are internal' b'terminated which causes problems for more then two devises off the scsi port' b'{a scsi chain is supposed to be terminated only at the begining and at the' b'end. any other set up causes problems for either mac or ibm}.' b'scsi-1: devices per scsi controller. 8-bit asynchronous {~1.5mb/s ave}' b'and synchronous {5mb/s max} transfers. difference is due to scsi-1 software' b'drivers. "fast scsi-1" is a misname for 8-bit scsi-2 in scsi-1 mode' b'{see scsi-2 for details}.' b'scsi-2: devices per scsi controller in scsi-2 mode. scsi-2 is fully' b'scsi-1 compliant and 8-bit scsi-2 tends to be implemented as a very fast' b'scsi-1 since it does not require the different controller interfaces in' b'hardware and software that and 32-bit scsi-2 do. transfer speeds are' b'4-6mb/s with 10mb/s burst {8-bit}, 8-12mb/s with 20mb/s burst {16-bit}, and' b'15-20mb/s with 40mb/s burst {32-bit/wide and fast}. since 8-bit scsi-2 can' b'use scsi-1 software drivers and hardware at 8-bit scsi-2 speeds and as such' b'is limited to devices sometimes it is mistakenly called "fast scsi-1".' b'16-bit fast scsi-2 requires a scsi-2 software driver and scsi-2 electronics' b'but can still use the scsi-1 ports. wide 16-bit and 32-bit scsi-2 require a' b'different scsi port, electronics, and software driver from scsi-1 {which' b'makes them more expensive than other scsi interfaces}.' b'mac scsi: asynchronous scsi-1 built-in standard since the plus. even though' b'apple developed some specifications for scsi controlers, the os scsi manager' b'needs to be rewritten to take full advantage of the features of both scsi' b'interfaces. as a result present scsi-2 macs use 8-bit scsi-2 as a fast' b'asynchronous scsi-1. presently quadras are the only macs with a scsi-2' b'controller chip built-in (digital review, oct v8 n33 p8(1))' b'though they lack some other parts of the hardware, like the wide scsi-2 port' b'interface. since other macs require a nubus card to use scsi-2, older nubus' b'macs had a bottleneck due to the speed of the nubus and cpu. rumor-some' b'cyclone macs {june} will come with a wide fast scsi-2 port standard' b'and have a rewritten os scsi manager.' b'ibm scsi: scsi-1 is not too wide spread yet, generally not bundled with' b'systems, except as add-on {eisa and vesa local bus adapters avalable}.' b'like the mac, 8-bit scsi-2 is used as a very fast scsi-1 by most controllers' b'out there. unlike the mac, ibm has no exact scsi controller specifications' b'which results in added incompatibilities for scsi.' b'' b'mac' b'memory expansion: with a few exceptions the mac has used non-parity 30-pin' b'8-bit simm memory expansion since the plus. while 32-pin 9-bit parity simms' b'could be used in these macs, only special iicis could make use of the parity' b'feature {by convension both simm types are called 32-pin simms}. the iifx' b'used 64-pin parity simms. the lc iii, c610/650 and q800 all use a new' b'72-pin simm that is accessable by 32-bits at a time and is used in ibms.' b'the mac does a complete memory check at startup by writing/reading every' b'memory location; if something is seriously wrong with a simm the mac will' b'not boot and give a sound chord indicating what the problem is.' b'since macs made before feb managed memory baced on data path, simms' b'had to be installed in pairs {16-bit} or in sets of {32-bit}. the centris' b'650 and quadra eliminate this with a new memory management setup that' b'allows memory to be upgraded one simm at a time. if the simms are the same' b"size are used then the memory is 'interleaved' across the two simms resulting" b'in a performance boost on ram access (macworld apr b'printers, adbs, and modems: built-in interfaces standard.' b'monitor interface and sound input: built-in on most present macs.' b'pds: available in se all present non-powerbook macs. 16-bit {se,' b"portable, lc, lc ii, classic line} and 32-bit. operates at cpu's mhz." b"maximum through put: data path in bytes*cpu's mhz {q700/900 c650:" b'4 25mhz 100mb/s; q800 q950: 33mhz 132mb/s}. standardized with' b'the lc and bus designs. with an adapter one nubus card can be used in' b'iisi and c610. problem: some cards have timing dependency which slows' b'through put down.' b'nubus mac ii: 32-bit, mhz bus clock, 1-to-1 transaction/bus cycle ratio,' b'and contiguous, hand-shake transactions