 key hooks for the mac os {quickdraw,' b'menu commands, print, mouse, scsi sound drivers, etc} in rom, which require' b'clone makers to use the rom chip or read rom on to disks {which requires' b'access to the proper mac since different macs have slightly different rom' b'chips; plus vs classic for example.} with key hooks for the os support' b'interface in rom, programers do not have to worry as much whether the disk os' b'has the necessary hardware commands or that those commands are consitant and' b'therefore can write smaller programs. this also allows apple greater control' b'over hardware-software standards and that the disk os can be smaller and, with' b'some of the tookbox command code in rom, with lower ram requirements then a' b'totally disk based os. macs use masked rom which is as fast as dram (jon' b'wtte).' b'6.0.7: single program usage base requirements: mb and dd floppy,' b'cooperatively-multitasking base requirements: 2mb and hd floppy.' b'features a gui, cooperative-multitasker [multifinder], standard program' b'interface, standard stereo sound support [snd]. network receiving part of' b'appleshare software is bundled with the os. has a 8mb ram barrier and is a' b'24-bit os. some third party products allow 14mb of virtual memory as long as' b'real ram is below 8mb.' b'6.0.8: with print drivers.' b'6.0.8l: system for some macs that require system 7.0.x.' b'7.0.x: base requirements: 2mb, 40mb hard drive, and de-facto standard' b'to run all features well: 4mb, 80mb hard drive, and {lowest present' b'non-portable mac configuration}. using up to 10.08mb {this is everything on' b'system disks} of hard disk space this has features plus program linking' b'within and between computers [iac], built-in server capabilities {filesharing' b'can be used by older oses using appleshare client software and can be' b'accessed by macs max; is more speed practical, iac requires 7.x},' b'virtual memory in machines with mmu{1.6 times real ram for least noticeable' b'iisi speed degradation}, drag and drop, quicktime built-in truetype' b'support. supports sound input [aiff and snd formats] for most present' b'machines. can access up to 1gb of true ram and 4gb of virtual memory and is' b'both a and 32-bit os. to use real ram beyond 8mb it must be in 32-bit' b"mode and on older machines requires the 'mode extension. apple's last" b"'free' os." b'7.1.0: with worldscript support, speedier, and less ram usage than' b'7.0.dot (macweek pc week to run in 32-bit mode' b"on older machines it requires the 'mode or '32-bit enabler' extension." b'marks the start of apple saling its mac os instead of allowing free upgrades' b'{bundled with new machines, for 7.0.x upgrades, otherwise}.' b'[the installer has a bug that when upgrading it may keep some old system' b'fonts from the previous system inside the system file. this can eat up any' b'ram benefits and cause other problems. apple itself recommends removing all' b'fonts from the system file.]' b'a/ux [unix]: needs 8mb ram {12-20mb suggested}, 160mb hard drive, and' b'a or equivalent to run. this 32-bit preemptive multitasking os' b'is large due to being unix and needing translators between it and the mac' b'roms. price: b'note: sound output was supported in oses to by many formats' b'including the following: snd, wave, asnd, fssd, qssn, smsd, soun, dc2d, and' b"dcfl. in the sound manager was optimized for the sound standards 'snd'" b'and aiff which causes some playback problems for the old formats, though most' b'still play.' b'' b'ibm' b'machiness have little gui code, data, and hooks present in hardware for' b'programmers to work with, so most of the coding must be provided in the os.' b'since hard disks were slow the disk os code is read into ram. in addition,' b'what little rom code there is also read into ram {a process called shadow rom}' b'this results in faster implementation since ram is faster then proms or' b'eproms. having most of the os code on disk has the advantage of being able to' b'better optimize the code given a certain piece or collection of hardware which' b"is harder with a rom based system due to the 'patches' needed. in addition it" b'reduces the need for and size of patches if a major revision of the hardware' b'support is needed.' b'side note: the ftc charged that microsoft formed a os trust by not providing' b'all feature documentation for its oses to developers outside ms and designing' b'its windows and dos apps to fail under os/2 ("undocumented windows") and' b'"there is deliberate code in [windows] nt beta which causes the install to' b'abort if os/2 boot manager is present" (gregory hicks, info-ibmpc digest v92' b'#201). due to a conflict of intrest by one member the vote of the ftc' b'judicial council for action against microsoft was a tie which resulted in no' b'action. rumors-the ftc will presue the matter, likely to the point of' b'choosing a new member or whole new council. in addition the government has' b'turned down microsoft\'s copyright of "windows" which would allow it to charge' b'a fee for developers using their hooks (pc week b'microsoft oses' b'dos has a 640k barrier with its own memory manager, a mb barrier' b'with third party memory managers. this 16-bit os requires that each program' b'must provide its own print drivers and be 16-bit {programs need to be dos' b'protected mode interface (dpmi) compliant and running on a 386dx [32-bit' b'protected mode] to break these barriers}. contains the gui shell present in' b'dos b'dos dos with the added features of a built-in file compresion, disk' b'defragmenter, debugger for the config.sys file. it needs a module for' b'networking {cost: through after that b'(byte april b'dos 32-bit dos. in development (pc week b'window runs on top of dos. breaks 640k and 1m barriers but still has to' b'deal with dos file structure. base requirements: 1mb, floppy and to' b'run well 2mb, hard drive, 386sx and fast display adapter 8-bit}. has the' b"equivalent of mac's qd called windo