ncludes printing]' b'wysiwyg printing can be a problem with either mac of ibm machines especially' b'if one sends truetype fonts to a older style postscript printer.' b'mac' b'hardware: built-in localtalk network port and a built-in printer port.' b'localtalk has moderate speeds kb/s) requires special connectors for' b'each machine and up) and can be run off of either the printer port {to' b'include very old macs} or the network port {standard today}. built-in' b'ethernet is becoming common but many older macs require a pds or nubus card at' b'about for each machine. these cards provide three connectors and' b'transceivers {thick, thin, and 10baset} for ethernet.' b'the macintosh quadra family and some centris models includes ethernet' b'interface on motherboard, with transceivers available. tokenring has been a' b'network option since b'software: appletalk {the suite of protocols} standard with mac os, which can' b'use variety of media types. appleshare client software included with the os' b'as well and can connect to file servers such as novell netware, 3com 3+open,' b"banyan vines, dec pathworks, apple's appleshare servers, system file sharing" b'machines, and afp servers running on variety of unix hosts. mactcp allows' b'typical tcp/ip communications (telnet, ftp, nfs, rlogin). a later version' b'will have unix x/open transport interface (xti) built-in by the end of b'(macweek third-party software to connect to nfs servers. dec' b'pathworks provides decnet support. peer-to-peer file sharing software' b'built-in to system (see os section). full server software is extra.' b'printing requires connection of the printer and the printer being selected in' b'the chooser. changing printers is by selecting a different name in the' b'chooser. the same is true of connecting to servers.' b'printing bugs: monaco truetype font is different then the screen bitmap font.' b'{quickdraw qx is suppossed to fix this and similar problems.}' b'' b'ibm' b'hardware: localtalk [not widely used], ethernet, and tokenring.' b'software: novell netware, banyan vines, decnet, windows/work groups, appletalk' b'protocols, and appleshare {subset of appletalk}.' b'each of the ms-dos networking schemes are, in general, totally incompatible' b'with the others. once you have chosen one, you are pretty much locked-in to' b'that product line from then on. windows/work groups is a little more' b'forgiving and removes some of this problem. novell netware is the biggest,' b'{~80 percent of the corporate market.} and in general is more powerful and' b"offers better control/management/security than appleshare, but it's also more" b'complex to set up and manage. this will change due to the use of the mac' b'finder and file management system by novell. (pc week b'infoworld dec macweek b'printing {very os dependent}' b"dos: if it's a single user, then you plug the printer into the parallel port," b"and don't worry about it {tweeking may be needed with poorly written" b'software}. network printing is not controlled by the system, but is mostly' b'implemented by the actual program, therefore performance varies from one' b'software program to the next.' b'windows 3.x: supports standard drivers and can do a good job of showing "jobs"' b'in the print queue, but it always lists printers as "active"... even if they' b'are not. this becomes a problem if there are several incompatible printers' b"on the same net, because there's no way for software to reliably determine" b'which printer is active right now. windows for workgroups is more mac-like' b'and intelligent about this.' b'os/2: mac-like; the os deals with printers, with apps making calls to the os.' b'printing bugs: due to poor programing some programs for all the above oses do' b'not have wysiwyg printing. this is the fault of the programs in question and' b'not that of the os involved.' b'' b'price issue: this is very dynamic with mac providing more build-in features' b"than ibm and ibm being more 'get only what you need' then mac and price wars" b'by both worlds.' b"the ibm machines' modualar nature prevents any kind of true hardware" b'standarization, which in turn requires oses and programs to be very complex to' b'handle all the variation in hardware. when one adds all the standard mac' b'hardware features to an ibm {built-in input/output sound support, scsi, pds,' b'built-in monitor support, built-in networking, standard mouse interface, and' b'nubus in higher machines} the mac tends to be cheaper then an equivalent' b'equipted ibm machine {especially since some ibm monitors can be used with macs' b"which cuts some more of the mac's cost (macuser aug b'some prices using some of the info in this sheet and macuser april b'all macs below come with a pds slot, vram, and scsi-1 built in. except where' b'noted, monitor is extra and a built-in monitor interface is provided {no card' b'needed except for 24-bit color display}.' b'ibm planned a 386slc/25mhz model with a 60mb hard drive and color vga' b'monitor {~vram} (macweek {sounds like a color classic without scsi-1,' b'sound support, built-in network support, fpu socket, built-in expansion to' b'16-bit color, etc}.' b'color classic: 030/16mhz with 16-bit data bus {~386sx/20mhz' b'equivalent}, fpu socket, and built-in monitor.' b'lciii: 030/25mhz {~386dx/33mhz equivalent}, and b'centris 68lc040/20mhz {depending on the program ~486sx/40 or' b"~'486dx2sx'/20[40]mhz equivalent}, built-in ethernet, 300i cd-rom, a" b'pds/nubus slot and vram for 16-bit color.' b'centris 040/25mhz {depending on the program ~486dx/50 mhz or 486dx2/50' b'mhz equivalent} with a pds and nubus slots. {ethernet, b'$3,559 {ethernet, {ethernet, cd-rom, vram for 16-bit' b'color}' b'' b'bibliography notes' b"'vaporware' is available in the digest/vapor directory by ftp on sumex-" b'aim.stanford.edu and was by murphy sewall {last issue: april b"'info-ibmpc digest' back issues are available from wsmr-simtel20.army.mil in" b'directory pd2:<archives.ibmpc' b"'dictiona